sols_latex:
Using the chain rule is much faster. Rewrite the function as

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle
f(x) = (x+1)^{-1}
\end{align*}

Then its derivative simply is

\begin{align*}
f'(x) = (-1)(x+1)^{-2} \cdot 1 = - \frac{1}{(x+1)^2}
\end{align*} (The
multiplication by 1 represents the derivative of \emph{x} + 1.)

Using the quotient rule works but is usually more messy. If you can
avoid using this rule and use the chain rule as demonstrated in the
first solution, do it. Using the quotient rule, the solution looks like
this:

\begin{align*}
f'(x) = \frac{0 \cdot (x+1) - 1 \cdot 1}{(x+1)^2} = - \frac{1}{(x+1)^2}
\end{align*}

